results.notes: I suspect these are mushrooms, though I have no idea what kind and am hoping others can help identify it. The mushrooms are tiny, with stalks of roughly 1mm diameter, stand roughly 30mm tall and have 2mm diameter inverted teardrop shaped caps. The best way to describe their appearance is like a mold that is consuming small shoots of grass. They were found growing only within the middle of a clump of grass. The blades of grass were also unique in that they were almost black in color, reflective, very thin/wispy, and easily matted (they did not rebound to original shape when touched). The clump was only approximately 4 inches in diameter. The whole arrangement was found among relatively dry, fibrous, slightly decomposed organic matter beneath an ironwood tree and nearby oak. It’s also the only plant/mushroom combo like this I found along the trail (or anywhere else for that matter).
